Japan Futures, Australia Shares Fall on Reactor Crisis

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-03-28T01:33:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-27/japan-stock-futures-australian-shares-fall-on-reactor-crisis-crude-price.html
(Corrects to remove erroneous reference to radiation levels
in the eighth paragraph.)  Japanese  stock futures  fell after
rising radiation levels hampered efforts to cool the stricken
nuclear reactors in Fukushima. Australian shares declined as
commodity prices slipped.  American depositary receipts of Honda Motor Co., Japan’s
second-largest carmaker by revenue, declined 3.1 percent after
the company said production in  North America  may be disrupted
due to a shortage of parts. Those of Canon Inc., the No. 1
camera maker, slumped 4.1 percent. BHP Billiton Ltd., the
world’s biggest mining company, dropped 1.1 percent in Sydney.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,400 in Chicago Match 25, compared with 9,450 in
Osaka Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,380 in  Osaka 
at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index fell 0.2
percent today.  “The problems at the nuclear plant got worse over the
weekend as more radioactive materials were detected, so
investors are likely to be in a wait-and-see mood,” said
Kazuhiro Takahashi, a general manager at Tokyo-based Daiwa
Securities Capital Markets Co.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index increased 0.1
percent today. In New York, the index gained 0.3 percent to
1,313.80 on March 25 after the pace of economic growth was
revised higher and Oracle Corp.’s profit forecast beat analyst
estimates.  U.S. Economic Growth  The  U.S. economy  grew at a 3.1 percent annual rate in the
fourth quarter, led by a jump in  consumer spending  that will be
hard to match early in the year as energy prices surge. The
growth numbers compare with a 2.8 percent estimate issued last
month, figures from the Commerce Department showed on March 25
in Washington.  As the worst atomic accident since Chernobyl entered its
third week, the Japanese government said soil near the Fukushima
plant would be tested for plutonium contamination. The
radioactive metal was used in one of the reactors and its
presence outside the plant would suggest fuel rod damage.  Radiation levels in water in the Fukushima Dai-Ichi No. 2
reactor’s turbine building were measured at more than 1,000
millisieverts per hour, Japan’s nuclear safety agency said on
March 27. That level is higher than the dose that would cause
vomiting, hair loss and diarrhea, according to the  World Nuclear
Association .  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 2.5 percent this year
through March 25, compared with gains of 4.5 percent by the  S&P
500  and 0.1 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 13.5 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.6 times for the S&P 500 and 11.1 times
for the Stoxx 600.  Crude oil for May delivery fell 20 cents to settle at
$105.40 a barrel in  New York  on March 25. The London Metal
Exchange Index of prices for six industrial metals including
copper and aluminum slid 0.3 percent on March 25, the first drop
in four days.  To contact the reporters on this story:
